[[File:HegewaldColonyMap.png|thumb|right|300px|Location of the Hegewald colony, situated directly south of [[Zhytomyr]]]]
'''Hegewald''' was a short-lived German colony during [[World War II]], situated near [[Zhytomyr]] in [[Reichskommissariat Ukraine]]. It was repopulated in late 1942 and early 1943 by the ethnically German settlers classified as ''[[Volksdeutsche]]''; transferred from occupied territories of Poland, Croatia, Bessarabia, and the Soviet Union to an area earmarked for the projected [[Germanization]] of the Ukrainian lands. The plans were prepared months in advance by the [[SS]], [[RKFDV]] and [[VoMi]], but major problems with supplies occurred right from the region's initial establishment.<ref>[[Lynn H. Nicholas]], ''Cruel World: The Children of Europe in the Nazi Web'' [https://books.google.ca/books?id=PeUKT6d9khIC&lpg=PT474&vq=Hegewald&pg=PT473#v=snippet&q=Hegewald&f=false pp. 336, 473], {{ISBN|0-679-77663-X}}.</ref> [[Heinrich Himmler]]'s original plans to recruit settlers from Scandinavia and the Netherlands were unsuccessful.<ref>[[Lynn H. Nicholas]], ''Cruel World: The Children of Europe in the Nazi Web'' p 330-1, {{ISBN|0-679-77663-X}}</ref>
==History== The initial plans were difficult to implement for a number of reasons including the reluctance and fear among many ''Volksdeutsche'' owing to partisan activities in the area. Elaborate guidelines were set up to prepare the locations.<ref name="cruel331">Nicholas, pp. 331, 474.</ref> The new settlers were to receive the homes of killed or evicted Ukrainian peasants, as well as their furniture, livestock, and food, and schools were to be built.<ref name="cruel331"/> This required a massive deportation effort, mostly on foot.<ref>Nicholas, p 331-2</ref> Most homes were in terrible shape by German standards. There was a considerable shortage of lumber, and general lack of winter clothing and shoes.<ref name="cruel474">Nicholas, p. 474.</ref>
The Ukrainian and Polish Germans did arrive on trains, having been forcibly removed from their homes, to be doled out plots of land and informed of their quotas.<ref>[[Heather Pringle]], ''[http://www.historynet.com/heinrich-himmler-the-nazi-leaders-master-plan.htm/1 Heinrich Himmler: The Nazi Leader's Master Plan]''</ref> They received use, but not ownership, of the land assigned to them.<ref name="harvest45">[[Karel C. Berkhoff]], ''Harvest of Despair: Life and Death in Ukraine Under Nazi Rule'' p 45 {{ISBN|0-674-01313-1}}</ref>
Neither the deported Ukrainians nor the ethnic Germans received more than a few hours' notice of their relocation.<ref name="harvest45"/> Despite damage to the houses, most could be made functional before snowfall.<ref>Nicholas, p 336</ref> Elaborate Christmas pageants were set up, deliberately irreligious, to celebrate the return of light and link it to the "dark powers" surrounding Germany, and gifts and food were provided.<ref>Nicholas, p 336-7,</ref>
All did not go as planned. The intended preparations were undermined by flinching of craftsmen, and neither food nor clothing arrived as promised.<ref>Nicholas, p 338</ref> Furthermore, many evicted Ukrainians returned to the area.<ref name="cruel339">Nicholas, p 339</ref> Efforts were made to continue, with the [[League of German Girls]] members being sent even when they had to receive gas masks and soldier escorts, but by November 1943, the inhabitants were in flight before the Red Army.<ref name="cruel339"/> These were the first of [[Flight and evacuation of German civilians during the end of World War II|massive flights from Eastern Europe]].<ref>Nicholas, p 434</ref>
==Villages== The colony consisted of 27 villages, all named in German differently from their traditional names; they were situated along the [[Zhytomyr]]-[[Berdychiv]] road. The existing villages of today are in the Ukrainian language.<ref>[[Wendy Lower|Lower, Wendy]]: ''Nazi empire-building and the Holocaust in Ukraine'', p. 176. University of North Carolina Press, 2005.</ref> {| width="95%" |- |valign="top"| *''Schröbelesberg'' – Зарічани [[:uk:Зарічани|(uk)]] *''Neuheimat'' – Пряжів [[:uk:Пряжів|(uk)]] *''Bubenhausen'' – Волиця [[:uk:Волиця (Житомирський район)|(uk)]] *''Neubiesing'' – Головенка [[:uk:Головенка|(uk)]] *''Pfenningstadt'' – Вишневе [[:uk:Вишневе (Житомирський район)|(uk)]] *''Heimkehr'' – Ставецьке [[:uk:Ставецьке|(uk)]] *''Troja'' – Троянів [[:uk:Троянів|(uk)]] *''Reichstreu'' – Озерянка [[:uk:Озерянка (Житомирський район)|(uk)]] *''Preuersdorf'' – Ріжки [[:uk:Ріжки (Житомирський район)|(uk)]] |valign="top"| *''Arbeit'' – Солотвин [[:uk:Старий Солотвин|(uk)]] *''Fleiß'' – Глинівці [[:uk:Глинівці|(uk)]] *''Au'' – Степок [[:uk:Червоний Степок|(uk)]] *''Zehnhub'' – Вершина [[:uk:Вершина (Житомирський район)|(uk)]] *''Neuposen'' – Кодня [[:uk:Кодня|(uk)]] *''Altposen'' – Кодня *''Bosfershof'' – Павленківка [[:uk:Павленківка|(uk)]] *''Wertingen'' – Вертокиївка [[:uk:Вертокиївка|(uk)]] *''Heinrichsfeld'' – Іванківці [[:uk:Іванківці (Житомирський район)|(uk)]] |valign="top"| *''Reinharding'' – Городище [[:uk:Городище (Житомирський район)|(uk)]] *''Am Hügel'' – Лука [[:uk:Лука (Житомирський район)|(uk)]] *''Klein Lüneburg'' – Ліщин [[:uk:Ліщин|(uk)]] *''Neu Trudering'' – Ліщин *''Mödersdorf'' – Млинище [[:uk:Млинище (Житомирський район)|(uk)]] *''Tiefenbach'' – Піски [[:uk:Піски (Житомирський район)|(uk)]] *''Sachsenhard'' – Скоморохи [[:uk:Скоморохи (Житомирський район)|(uk)]] *''Maienfeld'' – Сінгури [[:uk:Сінгури|(uk)]] *''Ichstingen'' – Миролюбівка [[:uk:Миролюбівка (Житомирський район)|(uk)]] |}
